WOMEN across Mzansi became new mothers as the new year started. In Mpumalanga, 14 girls aged between 15 and 19 gave birth while the total number of recorded births came in at 50. Health MEC Sharon Nkosi said the New Year babies, born between 12am and 8am, were 28 little girls and 22 boys. She said 42 of the mothers gave birth naturally while eight had C-sections. The first baby was a girl born in Shongwe Hospital at 12am to a 25-year-old. Nkosi said nine teenagers gave birth at the same hospital. In Gauteng, 150 babies were delivered at public healthcare facilities between 12am and 12pm. Health MEC Nomathemba Mokgethi visited Rahima Moosa Mother and Child Hospital on the morning of Saturday, 1 January to welcome the newborn babies and celebrate with their parents. She also handed out gifts.  New mum Elizabeth Thoke (34), who have birth at Jubilee District Hospital in Tshwane, said she was happy her child was healthy. She said it was her first child and she was scared, but the nurses made it easier for her. Busisiwe Gaborekwa (23) gave birth to her second baby. She said she was happy there were no complications and the baby was healthy. Senior nurse Maria Molamodi congratulated the mothers and staff for doing a good job. In the North West, 124 babies were born on New Year’s Day. This included a set of twins.  Health MEC Madoda Sambatha visited Tabane Hospital in the North West to hand over gifts to new mothers and their babies. Anah Masupa (27) from Lefaragatlha said she was grateful for her child. She also thanked health workers for doing a good job. Ayanda Tolbad (26) from Boitekong said she did not expect to give birth on New Year’s Day. “I was expecting to give birth on 18 January. However, my son was born healthy and I am happy,” she said.